<paragraph id="8BA636CAFFD08B095E8FFBE52664FB39" blockId="35.[189,1285,1143,1170]" box="[189,1285,1143,1170]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
This species can be distinguished by the 3 longitudinal dark strips on the prothorax (
<figureCitation id="13222A4FFFD08B095AA9FBE52796FB39" box="[1179,1271,1143,1169]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1853,1879]" captionTargetBox="[377,1222,265,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-15@20.[349,1238,265,1815]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 3. A–I. Habitus of males of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov. in dorsal view (part 2). A. E. mulanjensis Haran gen. et sp. nov. B. E. hessei Haran gen. et sp. nov. C. E. pedi Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. tsonga Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. hippopotamorum Haran gen. et sp. nov. F. E. incognitus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. G. E. oberprieleri Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. turneri (Marshall, 1935) gen. et comb. nov. I. E. rhodesianus (Hesse, 1929) gen. et comb. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6532977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6532977/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
